The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Tatas, M amp;M pledge funds
                                                                                                               Tatas, M amp;M pledge funds
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Tata Motors managing director Ravi Kant (right) and V. K. Jairath, principal secretary (department of industries) of Maharashtra, in Mumbai on Monday. (PTI)                                  
	Mumbai, March 31: Tata Motors and Mahindra amp; Mahindra (M amp;M) will invest Rs 6,000 crore and Rs 1,500 crore, respectively, to expand their operations in Maharashtra.        
	The companies today entered into separate MoUs with the government of Maharashtra.        
	Tata Motors will invest about Rs 6,000 crore over the next four to five years to expand its existing plants and also set up vehicle testing facilities in Pune.         
	The investments are expected to generate direct employment of 1,500 people at full capacity.        
	The agreement was signed by V.K. Jairath, principal secretary in the department of industries, Maharashtra, and Ravi Kant, managing director of Tata Motors, in the presence of Maharashtra chief minister Vilasrao Deshmukh.        
	Chairman Ratan Tata said, This agreement is a step towards realising Tata Motors plans to augment capacity at its Pune plants to meet customer expectations and demands both in India and abroad.         
	It also facilitates the setting up of vehicle testing facilities in Pune. Maharashtra has always been an integral part of the companys operations and we are delighted with the support that the state has extended to us.        
	Mahindra plan        
	Mahindra amp; Mahindra today signed an MoU with the Maharashtra government to increase its investment at the upcoming Chakan greenfield project.         
	The company will invest an additional Rs 1,500 crore along with the earlier promised Rs 2,500-crore in the project. The total sum of Rs 4,000 crore will be used to develop and produce the vehicles slated to be rolled out from the Chakan plant.        
	M amp;Ms greenfield plant at Chakan will make medium and heavy commercial vehicles and other products slated to hit both the domestic and global markets.        
	According to Pawan Goenka, president (automotive sector) of M amp;M, the company has decided to make Maharashtra the launch pad for its commercial vehicles.         
	The additional investment plan of Rs 1,500 crore, he said, will allow M amp;M to create a manufacturing facility for 300,000 vehicles.                                                                                                                                       
